Madame Oreille was a little woman of about forty, very economical, and with a very short temper.
It really pained her to see any money spent.
Whenever she had to spend any, no matter how necessary it might be, she slept badly the next night.
Her husband was one of the head clerks in the Ministry of Defense.
For two years he had always come to the office with the same old patched umbrella, to the great amusement of his fellow clerks.
At last, he got tired of their jokes, and insisted upon his wifes buying him a new one.
She bought him one for eighteen francs, and said, getting red with anger as she gave it to her husband, This will last you for five years at least.
Mr. Oreille felt quite triumphant, and received a small ovation at the office with his new acquisition.
But he had scarcely got home that evening when his wife took the umbrella from him, examined it, and nearly had a fit when she found it covered with small holes, just as if someone had emptied the ashes from a lighted pipe onto it.
She threw the useless article at his head, screaming out in a violent rage.
You did it on purpose.
You shall not have another.
Then she started one of those scenes, which makes a peaceable man dread his wife more than a battlefield where bullets are raining.
After the storm had raged for an hour, a ring at the bell saved him.
It was a friend whom they were expecting to dinner.
After Madame Oreille submitted the case to their friend, he was suddenly inspired.
Make your fire insurance pay for it.
The companies pay for all articles that are burned, as long as the damage has been done in your own house.
On hearing this advice, Madame Oreille calmed down immediately and said to her husband, Tomorrow, before going to your office, youll go to the insurance company and make them pay for the damage.
Mr. Oreille was very astonished at the proposal.
I wouldnt do it for my life!
Its eighteen francs lost.
It wont ruin us.
The next morning he took a walking stick when he went out.
Luckily, it was a fine day.
Left at home alone, Madame Oreille could not get over the loss of her eighteen francs by any means.
Every moment she thought of the insurance company, she hesitated, for she was very timid when she had to speak to strangers.
But the regret at the loss of the eighteen francs pained her as if she had been wounded.
So she said to herself:
Ill go, and well see what will happen.
But first of all she was obliged to prepare the umbrella so that the disaster might be complete.
She took a match and burned a hole as big as the palm of her hand.
Then she went out with the umbrella.
After a short while, she got to the insurance company.
She could not help noticing how her heart beat as she entered.
She stopped a gentleman and said timidly:
I beg your pardon, but can you tell me where I must apply for payment for anything that has been accidentally burned?
He replied, The first door on the left.
She went there and knocked at the door.
A clear voice said, in answer: Come in!
She obeyed mechanically, and found herself in a large room where three solemn gentlemen were standing talking.
One of them asked her, What do you want?
